<kml xmlns="http://www.opengis.net/kml/2.2">
<Document>
<name>Transfăgărășan — DN7C</name>
<description><![CDATA[<h2>Transfăgărășan — DN7C</h2><p><i>Romania · DN7C across the Făgăraș Mountains, Curtea de Argeș to Cârța</i></p><p><b>Ceaușescu's strategic Carpathian crossing; Top Gear's 'best road in the world.'</b></p><table style='font-family:sans-serif'><tr><td><b>Approx. length:</b></td><td>80 km (50 mi)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Drive time:</b></td><td>4–5 hrs</td></tr><tr><td><b>Best season:</b></td><td>Late June–October (closes November–June)</td></tr><tr><td><b>Watch out for:</b></td><td>Closed half the year, fog, slow trucks, sheep flocks, brown bears in lower forest, Bâlea tunnel can ice up</td></tr><tr><td><b>Track points:</b></td><td>208</td></tr></table><hr><p>Built 1970–74 by Nicolae Ceaușescu as a strategic military road across the Carpathians — the threat of Soviet invasion still real after Czechoslovakia 1968. The 90 km of high-mountain road were carved at terrible cost: officially 40 deaths, unofficially many more. Top Gear's Jeremy Clarkson called it 'the best road in the world' in 2009, and the tourism it generated has, in a way, redeemed the human cost. Bâlea Lake at 2,040 m sees an Ice Hotel each January–March (when the road tunnel is closed). The full road opens late June and closes by early November; check status before going. The view of the north-side switchbacks from a kilometer away is the iconic photograph.</p><h3>Scenic points marked on this route:</h3><ul><li><b>Cetatea Poenari</b> — Vlad III Țepeș's actual mountaintop fortress (yes — Dracula's castle). 1,480 stone steps to the ruins; the Bran Castle most tourists visit was a Habsburg fort he never lived in.</li><li><b>Vidraru Dam</b> — 1966 double-curvature arch dam, 166 m tall — when built it was among the world's largest. Walk across the crest; bungee jumping operates in summer.</li><li><b>Bâlea Lac</b> — Glacial cirque lake at 2,040 m. Cable-car access in winter. From mid-December to March, an Ice Hotel is rebuilt here each year — sleeping rooms carved from blocks of lake ice.</li><li><b>Bâlea Tunnel</b> — 884 m through the watershed — the highest road tunnel in Romania. Often the first part of the road to close in autumn, the last to open in summer.</li><li><b>North-side switchback panorama</b> — Pull off on the descent toward Cârțișoara — the road below stacks back on itself in the postcard switchback complex. Best light: morning.</li></ul><hr><p><i>Track geometry is interpolated between named waypoints — use a routing service to snap to actual road for navigation. Waypoints, scenic POIs, and notes are reliable.</i></p>]]></description>
